<Base
  title="About"
  description="What Past Time Ball is, where the clippings come from and why the team names matter."
>
  <article class="prose">
    <h1>About Past Time Ball</h1>
    <p>
      Past Time Ball is a hobby site. It reprints scanned newspaper clippings about old baseball
      and softball: game stories, ads, cartoons, feuds and the occasional great team name. Everything
      here was found in digitized public domain newspapers, mostly small-town papers whose sports
      coverage ran somewhere between literature and gossip. That was the golden age of the form and
      this site exists to pass it around.
    </p>
    <p>
      The clippings are the attraction. The commentary just points at the good parts, and the paper's
      own words are always better than ours. When a story says a man umpired a ball game and refereed
      a fight at the same time, there is nothing to add.
    </p>
    <p>
      The site is managed by the Bleacherite, who prefers the cheap seats and sees no reason to say more.
      The clippings also make the rounds on Instagram at
      <a href="https://www.instagram.com/pasttimeball/">@pasttimeball</a>.
      Corrections, tips and great old clippings are welcome at
      <a href="mailto:hello@pasttimeball.com">hello@pasttimeball.com</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Sourcing and rights</h2>
    <p>
      The clippings on this site are drawn from public domain newspapers, chiefly through digitized
      archives such as <a href="https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/">Chronicling America</a> at the
      Library of Congress. Every clipping page includes a citation to the original newspaper, with a
      link to the digitized source whenever one exists.
    </p>
    <p>
      The scans themselves reproduce public domain material and are free to share. The commentary is
      ours. If you spot an error in a citation or believe something is credited incorrectly, write to
      <a href="mailto:hello@pasttimeball.com">hello@pasttimeball.com</a> and it will be fixed.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
